Raw dev notes -- VisionMaker: Growing Pains and Pruning Gains

Okay, so VisionMaker. This project started as a pretty focused thing, basically a pipeline to help us annotate visual data, specifically for some material science stuff involving silica. Think of it as a smart assistant for labeling images or video frames, making sense of what's in them. The initial goal was to automate some of the grunt work for our ARAD team.

This past week has been a whirlwind of changes, honestly. It kicked off with getting that initial ARAD silica annotation pipeline up and running. Pretty standard stuff, just getting the basic flow in place. But almost immediately, we hit a wall with data volume. We're talking *a lot* of frames. So, the first big win was implementing SSIM (Structural Similarity Index Measure) for frame deduplication. I'd been thinking about it, jotted down some notes, and then just dove in. It was super satisfying to see it work – verified a ~40% drop in frames at a 0.95 threshold. That's a massive reduction in processing time and storage, which felt like a huge relief.

Then came the big architectural shift. VisionMaker was growing beyond just that one pipeline, so I bit the bullet and restructured everything into a monorepo with a proper per-project layout. That was a beast. It wasn't just moving files; it was about rethinking how different components would interact and scale. Along with that, I did a massive cleanup: dropped some old "junction" component that was more trouble than it was worth, standardized all the labeling naming conventions (finally!), and set up consistent subfolder reports. It's amazing how much mental overhead inconsistent naming can create.

The pruning phase was also significant. I went through and dropped some older `cluster` and `silica_filter` tools that weren't being used anymore, along with some outdated `reports/` and `references/` directories. It felt good to clear out the cruft, even if some of those tools were "my babies" at one point.

The final big chunk of work was a major tech upgrade: retiring OWLv2 for object detection and bringing in YOLO. That involved setting up both training and prediction pipelines for YOLO, and then restructuring the documentation to reflect all these changes. It's always a bit nerve-wracking switching core models, making sure the new one performs as expected and integrates smoothly.

Honestly, this week felt like a microcosm of software development. Started with a clear problem, built a solution, immediately hit a scaling issue, solved that, then realized the whole structure needed an overhaul because the project was growing. The monorepo transition was probably the hardest part – just the sheer mental load of ensuring everything still worked, and that I wasn't breaking existing functionality while trying to make it better. It felt like performing open-heart surgery on a running system. The satisfaction of seeing the SSIM dedupe work, and the clarity that came from the monorepo and cleanup, was immense though. It's a constant reminder that code isn't just about writing new features; it's about tending to the garden, pruning, reorganizing, and sometimes replanting entirely. I'm learning to embrace the messiness of growth and the discipline of cleanup.

Next up: Integrating new data sources and refining the YOLO models further.
